pan class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nataki526>Nataki526</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://av.gundamforum.com/avatars/anime/ahmygoddess/15.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(5/1/03 12:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1108.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://av.gundamforum.com/avatars/anime/ahmygoddess/15.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: well..</span><hr size=1> lol, well that would be a good idea! i can't believe i didn't think of that. how much japanese should i know, if i get to go?a couple useful phrases? everything? i know some things, but not tons. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=maimaipanda>maimaipanda</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Resident Panda</span><br> <font color=#336699>(5/1/03 2:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1108.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.sit.wisc.edu/~mamiller2/temp/pandatea.jpg height=146 width=130></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: well..</span><hr size=1> well, as they say over on bigdaikon, ESID (every situation is different).  I would think that this is a question the coordinator of the program will be better able to answer for you.  some programs require a lot of japanese, some none at all.  You'd have to ask them to be sure, though more never hurts!<br>
<br>
in the interim, if you want to improve your chances, it would be a good idea to cultivate a healthy interest and background in japan.  since it sounds like you have at least a year before the next program, it would be a good idea to start studying up on japan: join any japan-america friendship clubs in your area, get a japanese penpal/conversation partner, start reading books on japan, study japanese, and so forth. <br>
<br>
it is important that you maintain a broad range of interests in japan.  Exchange programs are looking for canidates that are well suited to life in japan, and who demonstrate a marked, wide ranging interest in the country, its culture and the people.  If someone asks you &quot;what interests you about japan?&quot; you should be able to provide several answers (and none of them should be &quot;anime/manga&quot;).  It would be a good idea to know basic things about japan's history, its political system, economy, culture and so forth.  I'm not saying you have to become a poli sci major or anything, but....<br>
For example, during my interview for the JET programme, I was asked a wide variety of questions.  Some of the memorable ones which stood out were:<br>
<br>
&quot;Do you know the last 4 emperors of Japan?&quot;<br>
&quot;What do you think is behind the recession of the past 10 years?&quot;<br>
&quot;What interests you most about Japan?&quot;<br>
&quot;Assuming you go, how do you think this experience will help you in the future?&quot;<br>
&quot;What do you forsee as some of the difficulties you will encounter in Japan?&quot;<br>
&quot;What aspects of the Japanese culture do you find most interesting?&quot;<br>
&quot;What is the name of the Japanese political system and what is its dominant party?&quot;<br>
&quot;Who is the prime minister of Japan?&quot;<br>
&quot;What do you see as one of the major criticisms of Japanese culture?&quot;<br>
<br>
and so forth.<br>
Now most of these questions will not be applicable to you, however, you should definitely be able to answer questions such as &quot;what are the last 4 emperors of japan&quot; and &quot;what interests you most about japan&quot; and &quot;what do you see as a major criticism of japanese society&quot;.  ESID, but if you can come up with good answers to the above questions, you will have reached a certain level of familiarity and demonstrated a desirable degree of interest which i am certain will make you an excellent canidate for any exchange program.<br>
<br>
now, you may be wondering where you can start, since you're not in college (and thus can't take any japan-related classes), nor have you studied abroad yet.  One of the best ways IMO to gain a good general background on Japanese culture, history etc. is to read a lot of books on the subject.  <br>
<br>
A few books to get you started (and these are just random suggestions, and by no means an exhaustive list; furthermore, some of these are quite dense, so don't feel compelled to chug through them all!):<br>
<br>
<br>
Ruth Benedict, &quot;The chrysanthemum and the sword&quot; (considered the 'classic' anthropoligical work on Japan)<br>
Karel Van Wolfren, &quot;The enigma of japanese power&quot; (one of my personal favorite books on Japan - very dense, but <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>highly</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> recommended)<br>
Alex Kerr, &quot;Lost Japan&quot; (a beautiful book on Japan and its current cultural/environmental destruction by a reknown expert in the field)<br>
Karl Greenfield, &quot;Speed Tribes&quot; (kind of a trashy, somewhat outdated book on the underbelly of the japanese &quot;economic miracle&quot;.  psuedo-fictional account, but an interesting read).<br>
Patrick Smith, &quot;Japan- a reinterpretation&quot; (general all around, easy to read primer on japan)<br>
Dianne Highbridge, &quot;In the empire of dreams&quot; (a hauntingly beautiful, fictionalized account of the life of gaijin expatriats in japan.  i loved this book.)<br>
Yuko Ogasawara, &quot;Office Ladies, Salaried men&quot; (a rather academic, but easy to read examination of gender power balance in japanese companies)<br>
Anne Allison, &quot;Nightwork&quot; (another academic examination of gender roles, this time in tokyo hostess clubs)<br>
Takeo Doi, &quot;Anatomy of dependence&quot; (an academic, but fascinating read on the concept of dependence in japanese society and the individual)<br>
David Bayley, &quot;Forces of Order - Policing japan&quot; (a scary, but intruiging look at the brutality of the Japanese correctional system with strong implications for the stability of the system and japanese 'passiveness')<br>
John Dower, &quot;Embracing Defeat&quot; (a very well done historical examination of post war Japan)<br>
<br>
and so forth. this is by no means an exhaustive list, nor are these neccessarily the &quot;best&quot; books to read on japan - it's just a random list of some of the books on my shelf.  If you need more help, or other suggestions, please feel free to post it up here!<br>
<br>
hope that helped!<br>
